Let’s talk about balance. I’ve been a little quieter on social media the last few weeks. Between annual planning for my job in Finance, teaching a bit more at Barry’s, and content creation, it’s felt like a whirlwind lately.

All 3 jobs are important to me, but the reality is that they’re often competing priorities. When I think of balance, it requires self discipline and knowing where you can give and take without reaching burnout. It’s frequently checking in with your mindset, health, happiness, and inner peace. It’s recognizing when you need to pivot. It’s being honest with yourself and drawing boundaries. It’s also having a good support system.

Balance isn’t fixed. It’s personal and delicate. It’s everchanging. And mastering it means keeping ourselves steady through those changes.

Unlocking new levels 💪🏼 I hit my one rep deadlift max at 225 earlier in September, which was a goal I’ve had for a long, long time. I am beyond elated that I am ending 2022 with a working set at 2x my body weight 🥹😭 trust the process, be consistent, and everything will fall into place. Here’s to unlocking new fcking levels in 2023!

Bryte focuses on restorative sleep by helping you easily unwind from the day with Somnify's multisensory relaxation experience that pairs sleep inducing sounds with gentle motions within the mattress. With Bryte's dual tailoring of their mattress comfort settings and Rebalancing actively relieving pressure points throughout the night, I’ve never experienced deep restorative sleep in such a comprehensive way. Bryte takes individual components of my current bedtime routine and combines them into one, while providing sleep and health metrics.

Maybe this is a sign for you to plan a staycation for yourself. If you can’t, don’t worry - you can also purchase the Bryte Balance mattress for your own home too!

Though we have the fitness modalities and instructors that are tried and true to us, it's important to vary and try new types of training/instructors every now and then. We all have our favorites, but there's a lot to be learned and discovered. It took me roughly 10 spin classes across 8 instructors to finally fall in love with spin. The same is true for other types of training.

Each instructor offers something different. Some specialize in running. Some specialize in pre/postnatal exercise. Some focus on rehabilitation and mobility. Some specialize in multiple modalities. I tend to program my workouts with an emphasis on heavy lifting and form...because it's what I love and do best. Particularly with women, we're afraid to lift heavy and get "bulky", when in reality, it's something immensely difficult to do. My goal is to empower women to lift heavy, feel strong, and know that they deserve to be in the same working space as men.

Remember, as we grow individually, so can our goals and areas of focus. That's why it's important to get to know more of your fitness community - so they can be there when you're ready to try something new or challenging. Let us know how we can support you. You know where to find us.

Most women focus only on training legs and glutes in the gym, but my favorite body part to train is my back. In fact, when I first started strength training, my goal was to have distinct lats running down my back. If you aren’t naturally curvy and have a petite frame like me, building your back will help give you the illusion of an hour glass shape. The back is often undertrained by females and most don’t realize how your back can change your overall appearance and posture.

I like to pair training my back with legs on pull days 2x per week. Below are my favorite back exercises:

1. Seated close grip cable rows
2. Wide grip cable pull downs
3. Reverse grip pull downs
4. Face pulls
5. Bent over rows (both bilateral/unilateral with dumbbell or barbell)
6. Pull-ups

We all talk about never skipping leg days, but here’s your friendly reminder to not skip upper body days either 💪🏼

Here is your rest day reminder. Choose a day to let your body recover, or your body will decide for you. What I mean by that is if you don't allow your body to recover and rebuild, your body will force you to slow down by being sick and take you out of your routine for days.

This has always been a difficult realization for me and I'm still working on it. The last week was extremely heavy with work and led to not enough deep sleep. I really felt it yesterday and despite every urge to keep up with my workout schedule, I forced a rest day and took a long walk instead. I went to bed early and slept for 9 hours, something I rarely do, but was much needed.

It's okay to put yourself first, slow down, and take a rest day when you need it. Mastery is when we are aware and acknowledge our limits. Our journey should be focused on growth and self love, not just relentless hustle.

#PremeraPartner Life is about finding the optimal balance between all the things you love and do. Most of you know that I work 3 very different jobs - I work full-time finance in the tech industry, teach part-time as a fitness instructor, and am a digital content creator.

Over the years, I’ve managed to find a rhythm that works for me by implementing measures that help keep me in check. Every day, I start my morning with gratitude journaling to help frame my mindset for the day and every week, I have therapy. Therapy has been vital in protecting my own peace.

Taking on so many things can easily lead to stress and burnout. Health and wellness is beyond just the physical aspect - it also incorporates mental health. @Premera Blue Cross’s Matchmaker™ for Behavioral Health is a service that provides access to both in-person and virtual care when you need it. Finding a mental health therapist can be hard and daunting, but Premera makes it easy by curating a list of therapists who match your needs and will take on new patients. Visit https://enroll.premera.com to find your Premera plan!

I often joke I give mini TED talks in my classes, but it’s very intentional. Usually it’s what’s on my mind or something I’m experiencing myself - and want to share with others if it helps them in some way. Today, it was about privilege.

In these classes with me, learn to appreciate the fight. Your high heart rate? It’s a privilege. The burning sensation your muscles are feeling? It’s a privilege. Being breathless after a sprint? It’s a privilege. Being able to move your body and train together as a team? It’s the ultimate privilege. Don’t lose sight of that. Now go on with the rest of your day by choosing to work hard and being your best.

Light is always around you, and sometimes you can’t see it. But the more you slow down, let things be and go, and trust that things are happening at the right time for you…not only does it become easier for you to see the light, but to BE the light. ✨

This past year, I’ve been very intentional with who I give my time to and how it is spent. Energy is currency, spend it wisely.

It’s important to practice gratitude, but even better to celebrate what you are grateful for.

November is the busiest and most stressful time for me. In my Finance world, this is when we build and lock our financial plan from the ground up for the next fiscal year. In other words, it’s my Super Bowl. Then you layer on top other side hustles, family, friends, exercise, etc. This time last year, I wrote about how balancing all of this isn’t glorious. There are trade offs, especially because I chose to live the life I am living.

This year, I’ve gotten better at being firm with my boundaries and saying no. Doing so allows me to keep my daily routine and habits that keep me grounded. Now more than ever, I’m very intentional with how I spend my free time and who I give it to because there isn’t a lot of it. And it’s all made possible with the strong and understanding support system I have, which I’m forever grateful for.

So just know that when I see you in my classes or spend time with you outside of the Red Room, I am grateful for you, and that I celebrate you.

New month, best you to end the year. What does the best version of you look like?
